Enter the letter of the graph of $y = -f(-x).$

extra.solution:
The graph of $y = -f(-x)$ is produced by taking the graph of $y = f(x)$ and reflecting in the $x$-axis, then reflecting in the $y$-axis.  The correct graph is $\boxed{\text{D}}.$

Alternatively, it can be obtained rotating the graph of $y = f(x)$ around the origin $180^\circ.$  To see this, let $(a,b)$ be a point on the graph of $y = f(x),$ so $b = f(a).$  Let $g(x) = -f(-x).$  Then
\[g(-a) = -f(a) = -b,\]so $(-a,-b)$ is a point on the graph of $y = g(x) = -f(-x).$  Since the point $(-a,-b)$ can be obtained by rotating the point $(a,b)$ $180^\circ$ around the origin, the same applies to the graphs of $y = f(x)$ and $y = -f(-x).$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair P, Q;

P = (1.7,0.8);
Q = -P;

draw((-2,0)--(2,0));
draw((0,-2)--(0,2));
draw(P--Q, dashed);

dot("$(a,b)$", P, NE);
dot("$(-a,-b)$", Q, SW);
[/asy]

question:
The function defined by
\[f(x) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
x + k & \text{if $x < 4$}, \\
2x - 3 & \text{if $x \ge 4$}
\end{array}
\right.\]has an inverse, and the inverse is defined for all real numbers.  Enter all possible values of $k,$ separated by commas.

extra.solution:
Note that $f(4) = 5.$  If we set $k$ so that $x + 4 = 5,$ then $k = 1.$  This value of $k$ makes the function continuous, as shown below.

[asy]
unitsize(0.3 cm);

int i;

for (i = -8; i <= 8; ++i) {
  draw((i,-8)--(i,8),gray(0.7));
  draw((-8,i)--(8,i),gray(0.7));
}

draw((-8,0)--(8,0),Arrows(6));
draw((0,-8)--(0,8),Arrows(6));

label("$x$", (8,0), E);
label("$y$", (0,8), N);

draw((4,5)--(11/2,8),red);
draw((-8,-7)--(4,5),red);
dot((4,5),red);
[/asy]

If $k > 1,$ then the function no longer has an inverse since it fails the horizontal line test.

[asy]
unitsize(0.3 cm);

int i;

for (i = -8; i <= 8; ++i) {
  draw((i,-8)--(i,8),gray(0.7));
  draw((-8,i)--(8,i),gray(0.7));
}

draw((-8,0)--(8,0),Arrows(6));
draw((0,-8)--(0,8),Arrows(6));

label("$x$", (8,0), E);
label("$y$", (0,8), N);

draw((4,5)--(11/2,8),red);
draw((-8,-6)--(4,6),red);

dot((4,5),red);
filldraw(Circle((4,6),0.15),white,red);
[/asy]

And if $k < 1,$ then the function has an inverse, but that inverse is not defined for all real numbers.  Specifically, the inverse is not defined on the interval $[k + 4,5).$

[asy]
unitsize(0.3 cm);

int i;

for (i = -8; i <= 8; ++i) {
  draw((i,-8)--(i,8),gray(0.7));
  draw((-8,i)--(8,i),gray(0.7));
}

draw((-8,0)--(8,0),Arrows(6));
draw((0,-8)--(0,8),Arrows(6));

label("$x$", (8,0), E);
label("$y$", (0,8), N);

draw((4,5)--(11/2,8),red);
draw((-8,-8)--(4,4),red);

dot((4,5),red);
filldraw(Circle((4,4),0.15),white,red);
[/asy]

Therefore, the only possible value of $k$ is $\boxed{1}.$

Let $r = 1994.$  The line joining the center $(0,0)$ to $(a,b)$ is perpendicular to the line joining $(2r,2r)$ to $(a,b).$  Hence, the product of their slopes is $-1.$

[asy]
unitsize(1.5 cm);

pair O, P, T;

O = (0,0);
P = (2,2);
T = ((1 + sqrt(7))/4,(1 - sqrt(7))/4);

draw(Circle((0,0),1));
draw(O--P--T--cycle);
draw(rightanglemark(O,T,P,5));

dot("$(0,0)$", O, W);
dot("$(2r,2r)$", P, NE);
dot("$(a,b)$", T, E);
[/asy]

This gives us the equation
\[\frac{2r - b}{2r - a} \cdot \frac{b}{a} = -1.\]Then $b(2r - b) = -a(2r - a),$ which expands as $2br - b^2 = -2ar + a^2.$  Then $2ar + 2br = a^2 + b^2 = r^2,$ so
\[a + b = \frac{r^2}{2r} = \frac{r}{2} = \boxed{997}.\]

