Let $\overline{PQ}$ be a line segment in set $\cal
S$ that is not a side of the square, and let $M$ be the midpoint of $\overline{PQ}$. Let $A$ be the vertex of the square that is on both the side that contains $P$ and the side that contains $Q$. Because $\overline{AM}$ is the median to the hypotenuse of right $\triangle PAQ$, $AM=(1/2)\cdot PQ=(1/2)\cdot2=1$.  Thus every midpoint is 1 unit from a vertex of the square, and the set of all the midpoints forms four quarter-circles of radius 1 and with centers at the vertices of the square.  The area of the region bounded by the four arcs is $4-4\cdot(\pi/4)=4-\pi$, so $100k=100(4-3.14)=\boxed{86}$.

$$\centerline{{\bf OR}}$$Place a coordinate system so that the vertices of the square are at $(0,0)$, $(2,0)$, $(2,2)$, and $(0,2)$.  When the segment's vertices are on the sides that contain $(0,0)$, its endpoints' coordinates can be represented as $(a,0)$ and $(0,b)$.  Let the coordinates of the midpoint of the segment be $(x,y)$.  Then $(x,y)=(a/2,b/2)$ and $a^2+b^2=4$.  Thus $x^2+y^2=(a/2)^2+(b/2)^2
= 1$, and the midpoints of these segments form a quarter-circle with radius 1 centered at the origin.  The set of all the midpoints forms four quarter-circles, and the area of the region bounded by the four arcs is $4-4\cdot(\pi/4)=4-\pi$, so $100k=100(4-3.14)=\boxed{86}$.

question:
A hexagon is drawn with its vertices at $$(0,0),(1,0),(2,1),(2,2),(1,2), \text{ and } (0,1),$$ and all of its diagonals are also drawn, as shown below. The diagonals cut the hexagon into $24$ regions of various shapes and sizes. These $24$ regions are shown in pink and yellow below. If the smallest region (by area) has area $a$, and the largest has area $b$, then what is the ratio $a:b$? Give your answer in lowest terms. [asy]
pair a=(0,0); pair b=(1,0); pair c=(2,1); pair d=(2,2); pair e=(1,2); pair f=(0,1);
pair g=(1,1);
pair h=(a+g)/2; pair i=(2*h+b)/3; pair j=(b+g)/2; pair k=(2*j+c)/3; pair l=(c+g)/2; pair m=(2*l+d)/3;
pair n=2*g-h; pair o=2*g-i; pair p=2*g-j; pair q=2*g-k; pair r=2*g-l; pair s=2*g-m;
fill(a--h--i--cycle,pink);
fill(a--i--b--cycle,yellow);
fill(i--b--j--cycle,pink);
fill(j--b--k--cycle,yellow);
fill(b--k--c--cycle,pink);
fill(k--c--l--cycle,yellow);
fill(l--c--m--cycle,pink);
fill(m--c--d--cycle,yellow);
fill(m--d--n--cycle,pink);
fill(n--d--o--cycle,yellow);
fill(o--d--e--cycle,pink);
fill(o--e--p--cycle,yellow);
fill(p--e--q--cycle,pink);
fill(q--e--f--cycle,yellow);
fill(f--r--q--cycle,pink);
fill(f--r--s--cycle,yellow);
fill(f--s--a--cycle,pink);
fill(a--s--h--cycle,yellow);
fill(g--r--q--p--cycle,yellow);
fill(g--p--o--n--cycle,pink);
fill(g--n--m--l--cycle,yellow);
fill(g--l--k--j--cycle,pink);
fill(g--j--i--h--cycle,yellow);
fill(g--h--s--r--cycle,pink);
draw(a--b--c--d--e--f--a,black+2);
draw(a--c--e--a);
draw(b--d--f--b);
draw(a--d);
draw(b--e);
draw(c--f);
[/asy]

extra.solution:
We add three lines to the diagram, connecting midpoints of opposite edges of the hexagon: [asy]
pair a=(0,0); pair b=(1,0); pair c=(2,1); pair d=(2,2); pair e=(1,2); pair f=(0,1);
pair g=(1,1);
pair h=(a+g)/2; pair i=(2*h+b)/3; pair j=(b+g)/2; pair k=(2*j+c)/3; pair l=(c+g)/2; pair m=(2*l+d)/3;
pair n=2*g-h; pair o=2*g-i; pair p=2*g-j; pair q=2*g-k; pair r=2*g-l; pair s=2*g-m;
fill(a--b--g--cycle,gray);
draw(a--b--c--d--e--f--a,black+2);
draw(a--c--e--a);
draw(b--d--f--b);
draw(a--d);
draw(b--e);
draw(c--f);
draw((a+b)/2--(d+e)/2,dashed);
draw((b+c)/2--(e+f)/2,dashed);
draw((c+d)/2--(f+a)/2,dashed);
[/asy] We have also shaded a triangle above. The shaded triangle is now divided into six regions of equal area by its medians. In similar fashion, the whole hexagon is divided into $36$ regions of equal area. Each of the original $24$ regions covered one or two of these $36$ new regions, so the ratio of the smallest to the largest area among the original $24$ regions is $\boxed{1:2}$.

question:
Isosceles right triangle $ABC$ encloses a semicircle of area $2\pi$. The circle has its center $O$ on hypotenuse $\overline{AB}$ and is tangent to sides $\overline{AC}$ and $\overline{BC}$. What is the area of triangle $ABC$? [asy]
pair a=(4,4), b=(0,0), c=(0,4), d=(4,0), o=(2,2);
draw(circle(o, 2));
clip(a--b--c--cycle);
draw(a--b--c--cycle);
dot(o);
label("$C$", c, NW);
label("$A$", a, NE);
label("$B$", b, SW);
[/asy]

extra.solution:
Reflect the triangle and the semicircle across the hypotenuse $\overline{AB}$ to obtain a circle inscribed in a square. The circle has area $4\pi$. The radius of a circle with area $4\pi$ is 2. The side length of the square is 4 and the area of the square is 16. So the area of the triangle is $\boxed{8}$. [asy]
pair a=(4,4), b=(0,0), c=(0,4), d=(4,0), o=(2,2);
draw(circle(o, 2));
draw(a--d--b--c--cycle);
draw(a--b);
label("$C$", c, NW);
label("$A$", a, NE);
label("$B$", b, SW);
label("$D$", d, SE);
[/asy]

